# Slab documentation standards

## Source of truth

- Always verify documentation against theme source code before writing.
- Use `.liquid` files, `{% schema %}` settings, and locale keys as canonical references.
- If required source files are not accessible, ask for those exact paths before drafting content.
- Do not guess block behavior, defaults, compatibility, or setting labels.

## Path-specific structure (audited)

- `slab/blocks/**/*.md`: Use the existing block-doc structure used across current Slab block pages:
  - `## Overview`
  - `## Common use cases`
  - `## Compatible blocks` (only when nesting is supported)
  - `## Block settings` (grouped tables by category)
- `slab/**/README.md`, `slab/README.md`, and `slab/SUMMARY.md`: Treat as navigation/index pages.
  - Keep them link-oriented with concise labels.
  - Do not force FAQ/Steps/Details on index pages.
- All other authored docs in `slab/` (for example guides, sections, getting-started, and general pages):
  1. Title
  2. Overview
  3. FAQ
  4. Steps
  5. Details

## Heading and formatting rules

- Use exactly one H1 (`#`) at the top of the page.
- Use sentence case for all headings.
- Keep headings concise and action-oriented.
- Keep heading levels consistent within a page.
- End all sentences with proper punctuation.

## Section quality bar for authored docs

- **Title:** Use the user-facing name from schema or locale translations.
- **Overview:** Write 1-3 sentences explaining purpose, context, and expected outcome.
- **FAQ:** Include 3-6 practical questions with concise, implementation-accurate answers.
- **Steps:** Provide an ordered, testable sequence using exact setting or UI names.
- **Details:** Include technical specifics such as defaults, conditions, compatibility, and caveats.

## Writing style

- Keep language clear, direct, and non-promotional.
- Prefer precise terminology used in the Slab theme and existing docs.
- Add examples only when they remove ambiguity or prevent misuse.
- If uncertain, state assumptions and request confirmation.
- When a page currently contains only a title, expand it with complete sections instead of adding filler text.
